  "overall_strengths": [
    "Strong at APK-level configuration problems that survive obfuscation: exported components, debuggable builds, backup flags, cleartext traffic, and many WebView settings.",
    "Good at surfacing hardcoded crypto artifacts because it combines API-pattern matching with bounded constant backtracking and ASN.1 decoding.",
    "Useful as a broad evidence extractor: URLs, libraries, reflection, JNI/native offsets, preference keys, and logging calls can all seed downstream reasoning.",
    "Resource/asset coverage is better than many pure-code scanners: it scans manifest XML, resource XML, string resources, HTML assets, JS assets, and optional native disassembly."
  ],
  "overall_limitations": [
    "Not a real taint analyzer. It traces constants and simple types backward; it does not model attacker-controlled data flowing from sources to sinks.",
    "No SQL injection, command injection, path traversal, authorization logic, token leakage, deserialization, or general business-logic bug modeling.",
    "No inter-component communication analysis and no implicit-intent reasoning.",
    "README is partly stale: it claims exported Service detection, but this snapshot has no Android Service export detector.",
    "Several detectors are visibly heuristic or brittle:",
    "`security-tls-interception` treats modern non-debuggable apps as if Network Security Config implies pinning, which is too optimistic.",
    "The same detector looks for `.//pins` under `<certificates>` and calls `pin.attrib(...)` like a function, so explicit NSC pin extraction appears broken.",
    "`manifest-cleartext-permitted` compares `.lower` instead of `.lower()`, so the manifest-side `usesCleartextTraffic` branch is effectively wrong.",
    "`manifest-manip-contentprovider` checks `//receiver[...]` when attempting provider private-action detection.",
    "Granularity is usually method-or-file level only. Android rules almost never populate `aff1`/`aff2`, so there is no stable line/column location for most findings.",
    "Some signatures are deliberately observational rather than vulnerability findings: open permissions, SharedPreferences access, root-detection style, reflection, libraries, URLs, JNI usage, native architectures.",
    "Several signatures have high false-positive risk because they are pure heuristics with no sink/source validation, especially logging, format strings, jQuery `.html(`, URL-like strings, reflection, library versions, and file-write detections.",
    "Taint relevance:",
    "Low.",
    "Explanation: the tool is mostly a sink/configuration matcher with limited constant recovery. Its output is still useful as taint-analysis prior knowledge (for example, WebView sinks, crypto API sites, logging sinks, SMS/device-ID accesses), but the tool itself does not perform source-to-sink taint reasoning."
  ],
